habitat_description:
In the United States, the burrowing toad only occurs in the lowlands of south Texas; In Mexico, the range expands south in the Peninsula of Yucatan. Its southernmost locality reported is Honduras (Behler and King 1979; Conant and Collins 1998). In the United States, this species only occurs in a limited area of Zapata and Starr counties in southwestern Texas (Dixon 2000). This species occurs from sea level to 600m, extending from southwestern Texas and northern Tamaulipas to Guanacaste Province in Costa Rica, Honduras, and Nicaragua (Lannoo 2005). 
Found in a variety of cultivated and forested areas as long as suitable for burrowing (Behler and King 1979). Soils must be friable and are usually found in cultivated fields and gardens (Garrett and Barker 1987). Habitat is technically dry rather than moist areas, but appear during high moisture events; habitats include savanna, tropical or subtropical, non-forested areas (Lannoo 2005). Breeding habitat consists of flooded areas and seasonal pools formed by heavy rains (Garrett and Barker 1987).
